And that's critical, because that's going to be up on the first floor.

412
00:34:08,109 --> 00:34:09,690
That's going to be a restaurant for the public.

413
00:34:10,090 --> 00:34:14,113
That's going to tie into our partnerships with Wynn.

414
00:34:15,037 --> 00:34:18,280
which is creating the casino up the street and developing job opportunities.

415
00:34:18,660 --> 00:34:25,325
That's going to tie into a whole pile of activities and revenue-generating activities that will support other programs.

416
00:34:26,285 --> 00:34:30,188
And that will free up space where Cafe Elektor is now, and we can do some other things with that.

417
00:34:30,228 --> 00:34:36,693
So this is a whole process of looking at how we can reconfigure space to our greatest advantage.

418
00:34:36,753 --> 00:34:41,376
Now, the print shop, because they don't use the big presses anymore, can now go down to a smaller place.

419
00:34:42,577 --> 00:34:46,499
We don't have to give them the big cavern that they have, because they don't use that anymore.

420
00:34:46,839 --> 00:34:48,639
That's not what printing is about anymore.

421
00:34:49,360 --> 00:35:07,506
So Dr. Ritchiell, for example, has created what we'll call clusters or academies, putting programs together, human service programs together, construction programs together, programs that deal with media and development together, so that they can interact with each other.

422
00:35:07,947 --> 00:35:11,688
So that a youngster, when they're trained, is cross-trained for more than one area.

423
00:35:12,781 --> 00:35:15,282
That creates great opportunities for our young people.

424
00:35:15,322 --> 00:35:17,824
Instead of being trained only in one area, you're trained in multiple areas.

425
00:35:18,424 --> 00:35:22,126
You may have noticed that we've virtually recaptured all the students from Minuteman.

426
00:35:22,967 --> 00:35:25,068
By next year, we'll have only eight students at Minuteman.

427
00:35:25,948 --> 00:35:31,371
We'll have saved a million dollars a year on that alone by putting these programs together.

428
00:35:32,712 --> 00:35:36,154
By bringing some students in from the outside, we're recapturing revenue.

429
00:35:36,699 --> 00:35:41,501
possibly projecting over two or three years, a million dollars a year in new revenue coming into it.

430
00:35:41,802 --> 00:35:49,746
This is going to help us weather the storm, whether it's federal cutbacks, state failure to pay, or some of the local issues, the priorities that we have.

431
00:35:50,386 --> 00:35:52,947
So these are ways that I think we're moving forward.

432
00:35:53,307 --> 00:36:03,232
And I believe that looking at our school at 50 years of age and looking for another 50 years from that building is a really good time to start and be proactive now.

433
00:36:03,352 --> 00:36:05,994
Plan, recognizing we've got to come back to you.

434
00:36:06,855 --> 00:36:08,115
You're not voting for money tonight.

435
00:36:08,136 --> 00:36:09,496
You're voting for planning tonight.

436
00:36:09,836 --> 00:36:12,597
You're voting to be proactive, to look and see what's possible.

437
00:36:13,458 --> 00:36:14,618
And that's what we were asking you to do.

438
00:36:14,658 --> 00:36:15,958
And I think it's a great opportunity.

439
00:36:16,359 --> 00:36:16,639
Thank you.

440
00:36:16,679 --> 00:36:18,359
Thank you, Mr. Superintendent.

441
00:36:18,800 --> 00:36:21,341
I agree with you with regard to the vocational school.

442
00:36:21,441 --> 00:36:24,322
I mean, my opinion, I think it's the hidden jewel of the district.

443
00:36:24,522 --> 00:36:29,023
I mean, there are so many great opportunities that are happening at the vocational school.

444
00:36:29,164 --> 00:36:29,924
You know, Ms.

445
00:36:29,964 --> 00:36:32,205
Riccio and her staff are doing a great job.

446
00:36:33,399 --> 00:36:38,403
I mean, there's so much demand now to go to the vocational school, and it's kind of the best of both worlds.

447
00:36:38,763 --> 00:36:41,485
You learn a trade, and you can still go to college if you want.

448
00:36:41,565 --> 00:36:44,928
So you really, you have the best of both worlds.

449
00:36:45,308 --> 00:36:46,109
It's an exciting time.

450
00:36:46,129 --> 00:36:48,911
There are more and more young kids going to the vocational school.

451
00:36:48,951 --> 00:36:55,476
So I think it's a great time to reinvest, not only in the high school, but in the shops of the vocational school.

452
00:36:55,856 --> 00:37:00,300
I mean, when you think about it, at the end of the day, our buildings are our most important assets with regard to

453
00:37:01,261 --> 00:37:03,042
the future of Method students.

454
00:37:03,082 --> 00:37:10,847
We need to make sure that they are first class and make sure that all of our technology is current as can be.

455
00:37:12,067 --> 00:37:16,490
You had mentioned previously about the potential for feasibility studies.

456
00:37:17,831 --> 00:37:27,316
So if we have to do a feasibility study, is that something that we would have to pay for or is that something that would be, would the MSBA help out with the cost of something like that?

457
00:37:27,376 --> 00:37:28,677
If we become eligible,

458
00:37:29,675 --> 00:37:41,782
We would then petition MSBA for a feasibility study for the specific projects that we determined were the priority that we wanted to go with them for or with.

459
00:37:42,602 --> 00:37:47,465
And they would reimburse us at the same rate they would reimburse the construction.

460
00:37:47,925 --> 00:37:54,629
So if the feasibility study was $500,000 and we're eligible for 50%, we'd get $250,000 back.

461
00:37:55,389 --> 00:37:56,810
We lay it out, but they reimburse us.

462
00:37:59,661 --> 00:38:00,341
I'm all set, thank you.

463
00:38:00,701 --> 00:38:01,462
Thank you, Councilman.

464
00:38:01,562 --> 00:38:02,142
Councilor Knight.

465
00:38:02,742 --> 00:38:04,062
Mr. President, thank you very much.

466
00:38:04,302 --> 00:38:06,163
Mr. Belson, thank you for being here this evening.

467
00:38:06,283 --> 00:38:09,024
I think you do a great job, and I appreciate you coming down here this evening.

468
00:38:10,684 --> 00:38:17,246
So I think it's safe to say that you feel as though going forward with this statement of interest is the most prudent course at this point in time?

469
00:38:18,286 --> 00:38:23,468
It gets us in the game, and it allows us to consider our options, which I think is really important.

470
00:38:23,828 --> 00:38:25,268
Earlier this evening, I heard you talking.

471
00:38:25,288 --> 00:38:26,328
You want to consider options?

472
00:38:26,369 --> 00:38:27,789
Well, you want to know who's going to pay for what.

473
00:38:28,433 --> 00:38:34,878
And if you've got somebody else who wants to pay for it, or will help you pay for it, you want to know that before you put your own money on the table.

474
00:38:35,779 --> 00:38:39,001
And this matter did come before the school committee, and it was endorsed by the school committee?

475
00:38:39,201 --> 00:38:39,341
Yes.

476
00:38:39,541 --> 00:38:41,023
I have the copies of the votes if you need it.

477
00:38:41,143 --> 00:38:42,664
Do you recall what the vote was I just offered?

478
00:38:42,684 --> 00:38:42,964
Pardon me?

479
00:38:42,984 --> 00:38:43,885
Do you recall what the vote was?

480
00:38:43,905 --> 00:38:45,026
7-0.

481
00:38:45,046 --> 00:38:45,306
7-0.

482
00:38:45,386 --> 00:38:47,267
So it's endorsed by the superintendent of schools.

483
00:38:47,327 --> 00:38:48,428
It's endorsed by the school committee.

484
00:38:49,009 --> 00:38:54,793
And the purpose of the paper before us this evening, as I understand it, is that you're really seeking permission to meet with the state

485
00:38:55,233 --> 00:39:03,536
to examine what competitive grant opportunities the Massachusetts School Building Authority has out there for us that the Medford Public School District may be eligible for?

486
00:39:03,816 --> 00:39:04,296
That's correct.

487
00:39:04,937 --> 00:39:15,640
And by submitting this application in the statement of interest, the Massachusetts School Building Authority in no way guarantees that we're going to receive money, and the city of Medford in no way guarantees that we're going to expend money?

488
00:39:16,061 --> 00:39:16,241
Right.

489
00:39:17,501 --> 00:39:18,622
Thank you very much, Mr. Belson.

490
00:39:18,742 --> 00:39:19,742
Move for approval, Mr. President.

491
00:39:21,263 --> 00:39:21,983
Vice President Mox.

492
00:39:23,600 --> 00:39:28,224
Thank you, Mr. President, and I want to thank Superintendent Belson for being here tonight.

493
00:39:29,205 --> 00:39:43,397
As the superintendent stated, Mr. President, this council over the last several years has approved many building programs within the Meffitt High School and the Meffitt Public Schools.

494
00:39:44,158 --> 00:39:46,920
And I think we've been very supportive as a council.

495
00:39:47,873 --> 00:39:53,219
My question tonight, Mr. President, is not regarding whether or not the high school needs improvements.

496
00:39:53,840 --> 00:40:01,308
I have two students that attend Meffitt High School, and I can speak firsthand that Meffitt High School, indeed, needs improvements.

497
00:40:03,290 --> 00:40:05,393
But my question to the superintendent is,

498
00:40:06,106 --> 00:40:23,569
My first question, back in September of 2016, the school committee, along with Mayor Burke, formulated a priority facility improvement list, of which they outlined $13,787,000 worth of repairs in the high school and our other school buildings, of which $10,100,000 was earmarked to Meffitt High School.

499
00:40:23,589 --> 00:40:25,349
Of that $10,100,000, Mr. Superintendent,

500
00:40:35,379 --> 00:40:40,263
What percentage of that $10,100,000 is in the current SOI?

501
00:40:41,004 --> 00:40:47,389
So I can't tell you that, because basically we listed almost everything that we possibly could think of in the SOI.

502
00:40:47,930 --> 00:40:52,934
So it really depends on what the state determines would be eligible.

503
00:40:53,675 --> 00:40:58,519
I would say most of the things that we listed on that would be something we would discuss with them.

504
00:40:58,959 --> 00:41:01,541
There may be some things that they would say, that's your problem.

505
00:41:02,767 --> 00:41:28,384
Okay, so, and the reason why I ask, Mr. Superintendent, is, and I'll get into this a little bit later on, but we were recently told three weeks ago that in order to build a combined police and fire center, that, and we were told this by our treasurer-collector and also by the mayor, that the amount of money we were looking to bond would cause the city to have to go into a Proposition 2 1⁄2 override.

506
00:41:29,164 --> 00:41:31,686
And that was one of the factors the administration stated

507
00:41:32,090 --> 00:41:34,191
why we couldn't bond for $38 million.

508
00:41:34,831 --> 00:41:47,815
So the reason why I'm trying to get some facts and figures tonight is I want to make sure that we're not going down the same avenue that the mayor and the treasurer-collector were so adamantly opposed to three weeks ago.

509
00:41:49,576 --> 00:41:51,776
And I'm hoping to get those answers from you tonight.

510
00:41:53,257 --> 00:41:56,878
So as part of the SOI, from what I can see,

511
00:41:57,683 --> 00:42:21,956
The capital plan that was put forth by the mayor and the school committee back in September of 2016 did not include a 500-student cafeteria, did not include a performing arts center for 1,000 students, did not include a fitness center, and did not include, from what I can see, windows and boilers.

512
00:42:23,646 --> 00:42:24,607
Okay, so let me.

513
00:42:24,647 --> 00:42:25,708
Now, if I could just finish.

514
00:42:25,748 --> 00:42:26,729
Yeah, sure.

515
00:42:26,749 --> 00:42:46,865
So based on the $10 million that was out there for other renovations, which included Medford High School flooring, which you mentioned had asbestos, which I would agree needs to be removed, roof replacement for $2 million, fire alarm system, which we know has been on the blink for a number of years, for $1,200,000,

516
00:42:49,809 --> 00:42:57,173
and $1 million to deconstruct the skateboard area and install modular units in the back of the high school.

517
00:42:59,054 --> 00:43:14,461
So at what expense is the addition of a cafeteria for 500 students, a performing arts center for 1,000, fitness center, windows and boilers gonna add to the 10 million that the school committee came out in September of 2016?

518
00:43:14,721 --> 00:43:16,782
Okay, so let me try and answer this way.

519
00:43:16,822 --> 00:43:18,083
They're all good questions, thank you.

520
00:43:19,158 --> 00:43:25,702
Personally, I allowed the planning team at the high school to put down some of their aspirational things.

521
00:43:26,802 --> 00:43:30,004
Now, I don't personally think I need a 500-student cafeteria.

522
00:43:30,765 --> 00:43:31,845
Personally, I don't think that.

523
00:43:32,306 --> 00:43:38,229
But I wouldn't tell my people they can't ask for it and let somebody else tell them, we don't think we'd fund that, OK?

524
00:43:38,689 --> 00:43:44,733
So I don't think that's going to be something MSBA is going to be interested in, because I think they already know we have cafeterias.

525
00:43:45,353 --> 00:43:48,755
And they'd say, probably, why don't you just put a coat of paint on and do some other things?

526
00:43:49,159 --> 00:43:50,140
So I don't think that's an issue.

527
00:43:51,141 --> 00:43:51,861
Point of information.

528
00:43:52,161 --> 00:43:52,341
Yeah.

529
00:43:53,282 --> 00:43:56,204
And I appreciate what you're saying, but doesn't that just muddy the waters?

530
00:43:56,224 --> 00:44:02,990
Because when I look at the SOI request, I'll be quite frank, it looks like we're building a brand new building.

531
00:44:04,511 --> 00:44:10,796
I mean, if you go through the list from roof to boiler to windows to flooring, I mean, it looks like we're building a brand new building.

532
00:44:11,396 --> 00:44:19,002
And I think to add stuff into the SOI that maybe you didn't agree upon as superintendent or thought it wasn't a priority,

533
00:44:19,335 --> 00:44:20,556
I think muddies the water.

534
00:44:21,617 --> 00:44:35,948
And what we have here, in my opinion, is a project that is probably closer to 30 or $40 million if we were to get total funding or total approval, I should say, from the state.

535
00:44:36,329 --> 00:44:38,050
And I know there's reimbursement.

536
00:44:38,390 --> 00:44:40,372
The number 55% has been tossed around.

537
00:44:40,832 --> 00:44:43,334
I talked to the state building assistance program.

538
00:44:43,935 --> 00:44:45,496
Don't bet your bottom dollar on 55%.

539
00:44:45,897 --> 00:44:47,658
In the past, we've received

540
00:44:48,045 --> 00:44:52,852
upwards of 59% for the science labs, but there is nothing set in stone.

541
00:44:53,452 --> 00:45:01,563
I know the mayor put that in her letter, but according to the school building assistance, they have not arrived at any funding percentages as of today.

542
00:45:02,064 --> 00:45:03,366
So in a,

543
00:45:04,758 --> 00:45:05,878
Good predicament, we could get 50%.

544
00:45:06,859 --> 00:45:10,680
But my question, Mr. Superintendent, why throw everything into the mix?

545
00:45:11,461 --> 00:45:14,282
Shouldn't we be looking at our major priorities?

546
00:45:14,622 --> 00:45:17,723
We should be looking at the major deficiencies in the school?

547
00:45:17,743 --> 00:45:19,244
Because that's what the SOI calls for.

548
00:45:19,704 --> 00:45:21,465
It calls for the major deficiencies.

549
00:45:21,945 --> 00:45:30,208
And you yourself are saying, I don't think our deficiency is adding a 1,000-person performance center or a 500-person cafeteria.

550
00:45:30,547 --> 00:45:39,636
But it may be the alarm system, or it may be an issue like Councilor Scott Pelly talked about, other building improvements that need to be done immediately.

551
00:45:40,456 --> 00:45:42,018
So I think that's the question.

552
00:45:42,058 --> 00:45:45,061
Why are we throwing everything at the wall right now?

553
00:45:45,121 --> 00:45:48,524
Again, as I said to you, the SOI is a planning document.

554
00:45:48,924 --> 00:45:51,427
It's to get you into an exploration process.

555
00:45:51,982 --> 00:45:54,483
and to find out what the state is willing to pay for.

556
00:45:54,923 --> 00:46:03,707
So you put down everything to talk about, and you find out that they're going to discard a few things here and a few things there, and maybe several things, and say that's really not important enough to us.

557
00:46:04,107 --> 00:46:05,087
But we'll find out.

558
00:46:06,688 --> 00:46:15,531
The document that you had in front of you is really a document that was produced in September, or early on, based on what people thought at that particular time.

559
00:46:16,132 --> 00:46:17,212
Different things emerge.

560
00:46:17,581 --> 00:46:18,862
People want to talk about them.

561
00:46:19,202 --> 00:46:26,365
There are some ideas that the headmaster has, that the vocational director has, that we put it down so that we could explore them with the state.

562
00:46:27,026 --> 00:46:30,327
Not because we necessarily think that they're going to fund all these things.

563
00:46:31,008 --> 00:46:37,951
We want to get into an exploratory process to examine what is possible for partnership with state funding.

564
00:46:39,011 --> 00:46:40,872
And then we'll merge the documents.

565
00:46:41,353 --> 00:46:44,154
The key thing you have to remember is we have to come back to you for the money.

566
00:46:44,998 --> 00:46:48,960
And any amount that we're going to spend, you're gonna prioritize along with the school committee.

567
00:46:49,640 --> 00:46:52,121
It's not gonna be the superintendent who makes the final call.

568
00:46:52,141 --> 00:46:53,642
The superintendent might make a recommendation.

569
00:46:54,222 --> 00:47:01,586
But you're gonna decide, and the mayor's gonna decide, and the school committee's gonna decide how much money you're willing to put on the table at any given point in time.

570
00:47:02,366 --> 00:47:07,088
But knowing what's eligible gives you a leg up on what's going on.

571
00:47:07,488 --> 00:47:11,710
And as far as the percentage goes, I know what other people are getting at this point in time.

572
00:47:11,770 --> 00:47:13,031
I know what the relative things are.

573
00:47:14,038 --> 00:47:16,420
The state's not going to commit to something before they see it.

574
00:47:17,040 --> 00:47:23,844
I know we fall in that basic line of where we would be eligible because I know what the economics are between the different communities.

575
00:47:24,625 --> 00:47:29,808
It doesn't mean that it won't, it won't go down a little bit because obviously the wealth of the community is increasing.

576
00:47:31,629 --> 00:47:31,790
Right.

577
00:47:31,930 --> 00:47:33,851
So, so Mr. Superintendent, if I could,

578
00:47:34,972 --> 00:48:00,370
So based on the laundry list that we're submitting in the SOI, and it is a laundry list, wouldn't it make more sense for us to prioritize what our needs are so we don't count on or have to count on some state bureaucrat coming back saying, you know what, Method, we know you need a fire alarm system and a sprinkler system and windows and an HVA system, but we're gonna give you a cafeteria for 500 students.

579
00:48:00,530 --> 00:48:01,331
They're not gonna do that.

580
00:48:01,991 --> 00:48:04,192
Mr. Superintendent, we don't know what's going to happen.

581
00:48:04,592 --> 00:48:12,496
But why not put together a list of what our priorities are and not just put together a list of, it sounds great.

582
00:48:12,936 --> 00:48:16,638
You put everything in there in the kitchen sink and say, hey, look, we're looking to get funding.

583
00:48:16,998 --> 00:48:19,880
It sounds great in theory, but it's not practical.

584
00:48:20,420 --> 00:48:23,301
I don't believe it's practical to put everything in the SOI.

585
00:48:23,721 --> 00:48:31,045
And I'd rather see, like Councilor Scott Pelley mentioned, a list of what our top priorities are and have them go through our top priorities

586
00:48:31,444 --> 00:48:47,529
Mr. Superintendent, and then make a selection from our top priorities, and if a 500 student cafeteria is not on the top of your priority list, as superintendent of the school committee's priority list, then that should be at the bottom of the list.

587
00:48:48,649 --> 00:48:52,010
Or not on the list at all, Mr. Superintendent.

588
00:48:52,130 --> 00:48:58,972
I hear what you're saying, but my experience tells me in meeting, because I've had these meetings before, as you know, we've had science labs,

589
00:48:59,274 --> 00:49:00,594
We've built new buildings and so on.

590
00:49:00,854 --> 00:49:09,997
My experience tells me that when we sit down with them, we'll focus in on the things that are high priority first, and then we'll look at whether these things, any of these other things are possible.

591
00:49:10,857 --> 00:49:16,699
But they know the difference between a fire alarm system and a roof and a cafeteria.

592
00:49:17,439 --> 00:49:20,700
They know the difference, and they know where we would like to go first.

593
00:49:21,100 --> 00:49:28,882
This is an attempt to give everybody, every stakeholder who is involved in the planning process of putting an SOI together a chance to be heard,

594
00:49:30,097 --> 00:49:34,503
rather than say your idea is not worth being explored with the state.

595
00:49:34,903 --> 00:49:36,185
We're giving them a chance to be heard.

596
00:49:36,706 --> 00:49:42,073
But you know and I know that the state will zero in on firearms and roofs.

597
00:49:42,777 --> 00:49:46,019
and heating systems long before they worry about the cafeteria.

598
00:49:46,059 --> 00:49:46,199
Right.

599
00:49:46,699 --> 00:49:57,785
And if we were so concerned of having every stakeholder seat at the table, why don't we see the middle school and elementary schools as a separate SOI, Mr. Superintendent, which can be done.

600
00:49:57,805 --> 00:50:08,571
I'm sure you know that as superintendent, uh, there was no mention about the needs of, as council Longo Kern mentioned, the secondary schools, um, within this and no, it shouldn't be.

601
00:50:08,591 --> 00:50:10,052
Cause this is a high school proposal.

602
00:50:10,551 --> 00:50:16,135
But there's also proposals that are in need, as you know, in our other schools, in dire need.

603
00:50:16,656 --> 00:50:29,726
So my question is then, my second question, Mr. President, is the fact that I realize the order which takes place is you submit the SOI.

604
00:50:30,486 --> 00:50:34,049
I didn't realize after you submit the SOI, then you go sit down with the state people.

605
00:50:34,469 --> 00:50:35,050
I didn't know that.

606
00:50:35,090 --> 00:50:37,952
You're telling me you now then go sit down with the state people.

607
00:50:39,927 --> 00:50:41,227
What do you do, compromise with them?

608
00:50:41,628 --> 00:50:51,731
You sit down and you go over and they'll tell you what they would consider to be priorities, what they would consider to be something that they would consider to be of concern to them, what they would like to fund.

609
00:50:52,491 --> 00:50:56,333
I mean, after all, they're accountable to their funding agency and their board as well.

610
00:50:56,853 --> 00:51:04,636
So I think that they'd be more interested in a fire alarm system, a roof, heating systems, more so than some of the other things.

611
00:51:04,716 --> 00:51:07,437
But we're giving them all these things and they might say,

612
00:51:08,722 --> 00:51:09,903
We're doing something with this.

613
00:51:10,163 --> 00:51:13,146
Who knew a few years ago that they were going to be funding science labs?

614
00:51:13,686 --> 00:51:16,129
But we put it in front of them, and we got it.

615
00:51:17,190 --> 00:51:19,331
You know, you have to try all these things.

616
00:51:19,351 --> 00:51:21,431
You put it in front of them and say, are you interested in this?

617
00:51:22,111 --> 00:51:25,012
Could you consider this to be a reasonable investment?

618
00:51:25,732 --> 00:51:29,613
Maybe someone's going to say, yes, you know, we've got an interest in this at this point in time.

619
00:51:30,133 --> 00:51:33,414
So we're moving forward with a planning process.

620
00:51:33,454 --> 00:51:42,057
That's all we're doing tonight, asking you to allow us to go forward proactively and find out what the state wants to prioritize in our community.

621
00:51:42,637 --> 00:51:43,397
And this is going to take,

622
00:51:44,413 --> 00:51:46,794
probably two to three years to actually actualize.

623
00:51:47,194 --> 00:51:53,516
And in the meantime, that will inform our other capital planning that may have to be locally funded.

624
00:51:54,457 --> 00:51:58,418
And we will form also our maintenance issues, which will be locally funded.

625
00:51:59,499 --> 00:52:01,660
And then grant applications we make.

626
00:52:01,700 --> 00:52:10,003
If someone were to say we can't get grants for this, for example, we're building the Culinary Arts and Hospitality Center, that wasn't gonna be funded by MSBA.

627
00:52:12,017 --> 00:52:13,458
But we got a grant to do it.

628
00:52:14,479 --> 00:52:16,220
So we have to know where we have to go.

629
00:52:16,240 --> 00:52:20,324
We have to know what's possible under what set of funding and what's possible under other sets of funding.

630
00:52:20,964 --> 00:52:21,985
And then we can then lay it out.

631
00:52:22,445 --> 00:52:27,169
And of course, we're going to have to work with you and the school committee for any kind of local money.

632
00:52:27,742 --> 00:52:30,443
that's going to be needed to move the project forward.

633
00:52:30,864 --> 00:52:34,645
This isn't you say yes tonight, and I go off and do whatever I want.

634
00:52:35,106 --> 00:52:39,788
This is you say yes tonight, we get the process going, and then we come back to you and sit down.

635
00:52:39,848 --> 00:52:47,051
And it should be a robust process, because the city wants to move forward on some good projects, not only in the schools, but in the city.

636
00:52:47,652 --> 00:52:48,712
And we look forward to that.

637
00:52:50,113 --> 00:52:54,735
So if I could, Mr. Superintendent, I know you're probably not prepared tonight to put a

638
00:52:55,159 --> 00:53:07,754
a dollar amount onto your deficiency request, but you were able to put a dollar amount back in September of 2016 on the laundry list of items that you mentioned needed repair at the high school.

639
00:53:08,134 --> 00:53:12,940
Are you prepared tonight to put a dollar amount on your SOI request to the state?

640
00:53:12,960 --> 00:53:14,742
No, because I don't know, you know,

641
00:53:15,558 --> 00:53:18,300
the extent to which any of these things would be funded.

642
00:53:18,340 --> 00:53:19,020
But I do know.

643
00:53:19,460 --> 00:53:20,481
Now, I'm not talking about funding.

644
00:53:20,921 --> 00:53:23,363
What is the actual cost of your SOI request?

645
00:53:23,523 --> 00:53:31,628
You know, I wouldn't want to give you a guess right now, because quite frankly, it depends on the extent to which you do them.

646
00:53:31,908 --> 00:53:38,312
And any one of these things might be a partial thing, maybe some windows, maybe some doors, and maybe all doors.

647
00:53:40,173 --> 00:53:42,294
I don't think we can do that right now.

648
00:53:42,634 --> 00:53:44,776
When we get back from a planning process,

649
00:53:45,531 --> 00:53:49,113
and we get to a financial phase, then we can do that.

650
00:53:49,594 --> 00:53:53,796
That's the most prudent way to do it, not to throw speculative numbers out there right now.

651
00:53:54,337 --> 00:53:58,559
And if people come and say, look, that's too much at any one time, then that'll be too much at any one time.

652
00:53:59,320 --> 00:54:14,069
Okay, so what you're asking then is the council to let you go forward, and then in deliberations, when you submit your SOI with the state, you'll go back and forth with the state, and they'll determine what projects will be done or approved,

653
00:54:14,885 --> 00:54:27,492
And if they come back and say, you know what, Method, we like everything in your SOI, there's been a lack of requests for school building assistance this year, and we're gonna fund you for $60 million, Method.

654
00:54:27,792 --> 00:54:30,453
Congratulations, and we're even gonna give you half.

655
00:54:31,334 --> 00:54:34,816
We're gonna give you 30 million, so you're gonna have to bond for 30 million.

656
00:54:35,196 --> 00:54:42,660
Are you prepared to come back to this city, Mr. Superintendent, with a $30 million bond request within the next two to three years?

657
00:54:43,595 --> 00:54:54,561
I'd be prepared to come back to you to tell you what your options are and to allow you to decide what the finances of this city is willing to support in support of your public schools.

658
00:54:54,961 --> 00:54:56,062
That's all just like anything else.

659
00:54:56,082 --> 00:54:57,022
We come to you with a budget.

660
00:54:57,182 --> 00:54:59,223
We come to you with other kinds of financial things.

661
00:54:59,523 --> 00:55:02,345
You can tell us how much more you want to put into it.

662
00:55:02,405 --> 00:55:07,027
But you know, for example, in five or six years, you're going to replace a roof at the high school.

663
00:55:07,247 --> 00:55:07,988
You are going to do it.

664
00:55:08,528 --> 00:55:09,749
The question is, who's going to pay for it?

665
00:55:10,558 --> 00:55:15,981
But if we are eligible to get somebody to share that with us, why not find out now?

666
00:55:16,882 --> 00:55:21,464
You know that there are some heating things that we wanna do at the high school that we should do.

667
00:55:22,185 --> 00:55:24,886
If you don't do them in the next few years, you'll end up paying for it.

668
00:55:25,206 --> 00:55:27,808
So we should find out if we have a partner.

669
00:55:27,828 --> 00:55:28,789
And so on and so forth.

670
00:55:29,129 --> 00:55:31,710
We know that technology is moving at a rapid rate.

671
00:55:32,891 --> 00:55:37,974
And if we know that it's gonna be expensive to increase all the technology that's gonna be required of public schools,

672
00:55:39,083 --> 00:55:43,025
So if someone's willing to partner with us, great.

673
00:55:43,065 --> 00:55:43,665
You'll know that.

674
00:55:44,365 --> 00:55:45,385
That gives you those things.

675
00:55:45,465 --> 00:55:54,429
But you can decide that I'm not interested in a performing arts center, and I'm not interested in an expanded cafeteria, and I don't really care about some other things you're interested in.

676
00:55:54,469 --> 00:56:00,391
So even though someone's willing to partner with us, it's off the table for Medford because we have other things we want to do.

677
00:56:01,292 --> 00:56:02,792
My job is to give you options.

678
00:56:03,272 --> 00:56:05,373
My job is to give you an opportunity to look at it.

679
00:56:06,073 --> 00:56:07,434
And who's going to make that decision?

680
00:56:07,899 --> 00:56:12,441
So let's just say, in a perfect scenario, the state comes back and said, Meffitt, we're giving you everything you wanted.

681
00:56:13,181 --> 00:56:14,782
Who ultimately is going to make that decision?

682
00:56:14,802 --> 00:56:17,123
Are you saying it's this council that's going to sit there?

683
00:56:17,183 --> 00:56:22,085
School committee, mayor, and council are the arbiters of dollars and cents.

684
00:56:22,265 --> 00:56:22,465
Right.

685
00:56:22,525 --> 00:56:26,607
But we ultimately have the final funding say, Mr. Superintendent.

686
00:56:27,027 --> 00:56:34,710
So you think this council is going to sit back after the SOI is put in, and if everything works out perfectly, and they come to us and they pay for half,

687
00:56:35,410 --> 00:56:37,031
And we're getting everything we want.

688
00:56:37,431 --> 00:56:48,518
You think the City Council is going to sit here and start slashing different items in the budget to make sure that we don't have a Proposition 2.5 override?

689
00:56:49,088 --> 00:56:50,729
Is that what you expect this council to do?

690
00:56:51,049 --> 00:56:53,171
And that's my questioning, Mr. Superintendent.

691
00:56:53,531 --> 00:56:57,514
Why are we throwing everything at the wall when we know what deficiencies we have?

692
00:56:57,774 --> 00:57:00,616
We should prioritize them right now and move forward on them.

693
00:57:00,816 --> 00:57:02,117
This program is going nowhere.

694
00:57:02,517 --> 00:57:06,139
So to make people believe that, hey, that's, you know, let's get a partner today.

695
00:57:06,460 --> 00:57:09,642
We can get a partner today, tomorrow, next year, the year after.

696
00:57:09,882 --> 00:57:14,705
This program has been around for years and we've taken advantage for many, many years, Mr. Superintendent.

697
00:57:15,197 --> 00:57:25,500
You know, we got, for a core program, 59.79%, it doesn't give the year, 2008, I'm sorry.

698
00:57:25,900 --> 00:57:30,481
Then the science labs, we got 59%, $6 million reimbursement.

699
00:57:31,201 --> 00:57:36,783
Then the accelerated repair, $2,409,000, they gave us a million dollars.

700
00:57:37,143 --> 00:57:39,844
So I know we've been great partners with the state.

701
00:57:40,384 --> 00:57:43,945
My concern is, eventually, because I've been on this council a number of years,

702
00:57:44,453 --> 00:57:47,475
is that eventually the issue's gonna come back before this council.

703
00:57:48,235 --> 00:57:52,198
And we're gonna be the ones that are gonna be sitting there saying, geez, you know what?

704
00:57:52,558 --> 00:57:57,020
The state wants to give us all this money, but the city council doesn't want to approve it.

705
00:57:57,421 --> 00:58:00,662
They want to pay half of this and this and this, but they don't want to approve it.

706
00:58:00,943 --> 00:58:03,304
And we know what the purse strings are, Mr. Superintendent.

707
00:58:03,604 --> 00:58:13,590
When we hear from the mayor three weeks ago saying that she can't afford to do a combined center for police and fire, because according to her and the treasurer-collector,

708
00:58:14,410 --> 00:58:20,273
that the school bonds will be coming offline in the year 2022, which is five years.

709
00:58:20,773 --> 00:58:25,795
And she said we can't afford the spending that we want to do for a combined center until 2022.

710
00:58:27,776 --> 00:58:31,778
Now you're telling us that this project, they could be looking for funding maybe two or three years.

711
00:58:32,098 --> 00:58:32,658
Is that correct?

712
00:58:33,438 --> 00:58:41,862
Well, what I'm telling you is I'm telling you it'll take two to three years to get through the process to actually get construction going on something, any project that gets approved.

713
00:58:42,336 --> 00:58:50,300
and the like, but we won't even get to design feasibility and design until we come back here and talk about what the state is interested in.

714
00:58:50,760 --> 00:58:58,244
And in the feasibility period, that's when you will make some decisions before we actually go forward with a final number.

715
00:58:58,984 --> 00:59:03,367
I mean, the reality is that some things will be done over five years, some things may be done over 10 years.

716
00:59:04,580 --> 00:59:09,162
The reality is, is to find out what we can get some funding for and what we can get support for.

717
00:59:09,482 --> 00:59:09,862
Correct.

718
00:59:10,242 --> 00:59:11,242
And that is the reality.

719
00:59:11,262 --> 00:59:12,523
And that, that's why I'm bringing this up.

720
00:59:12,823 --> 00:59:14,263
There is a reality behind this.

721
00:59:15,064 --> 00:59:27,208
And when I hear from the administration and the treasurer collector saying that we can't afford any more bonds other than what we just did for the police department until the year 2022, unless we want to look at a prop two and a half override.

722
00:59:27,702 --> 00:59:31,463
I think every member of this council and every citizen should be concerned about it.

723
00:59:31,903 --> 00:59:35,203
And we should have a handle on what we're potentially looking at.

724
00:59:35,223 --> 00:59:41,045
And from what you're telling me now, the process is, you just submit, you really don't know what the dollar amount will be.

725
00:59:41,065 --> 00:59:45,345
You just submit it, you hope for the best, and when it comes back, it comes back.

726
00:59:46,005 --> 00:59:48,286
And then at that point, you look at the financials.

727
00:59:48,666 --> 00:59:53,987
And what I'm telling you is, the mayor just told us three weeks ago, we're looking at five years down the line.

728
00:59:55,320 --> 00:59:58,203
And that doesn't seem what we're looking for for these schools.

729
00:59:58,703 --> 00:59:59,764
I mean, I read the SOI.

730
00:59:59,784 --> 01:00:09,372
It says an SOI should only be filed for a facility where a district has the ability to gain the proper local approvals and a fund to fund a project in the next two years.

731
01:00:10,893 --> 01:00:14,476
So they're putting, you know, they want to see commitment.

732
01:00:14,716 --> 01:00:19,140
That's why they're asking for a vote, the school committee, the council, and they want to see a funding commitment.

733
01:00:20,108 --> 01:00:22,253
And we're at such an early stage.

734
01:00:22,493 --> 01:00:23,475
I know that.

735
01:00:23,656 --> 01:00:30,230
And quite frankly, look, you get hit with a lot of decisions that require you to make tough decisions on money, on

736
01:00:30,947 --> 01:00:33,348
policies, on zoning, on any number of issues.

737
01:00:33,908 --> 01:00:40,232
You can't hide from, not that you want to, from making tough decisions that make some people happy and some people less happy.

738
01:00:40,352 --> 01:00:49,496
With all due respect, you just stated that you put things in this SOI that you didn't want in there because you were hiding from dealing with other people at the table.

739
01:00:49,616 --> 01:00:51,257
So don't say people are hiding, Mr. Superintendent.

740
01:00:51,437 --> 01:00:54,098
I said I respected the right of the planning team to forward things

741
01:00:57,721 --> 01:01:05,086
that they consider to be important to them because I want to respect my administrative team and the teachers and others who participate.

742
01:01:05,366 --> 01:01:10,050
You're the educational leader of this community, Mr. Superintendent.

743
01:01:10,350 --> 01:01:11,911
And I like the participation of people.

744
01:01:11,931 --> 01:01:13,532
I don't have to make all the decisions myself.

745
01:01:14,673 --> 01:01:19,957
But the reality is that nothing is going to go forward financially unless you decide you can afford it.

746
01:01:20,745 --> 01:01:22,166
Nothing's going to go forward.

747
01:01:22,186 --> 01:01:25,307
We're trying to explore who wants to partner with us.

748
01:01:26,107 --> 01:01:30,929
And you know that the most important things will be systems that are important to the school.

749
01:01:30,969 --> 01:01:36,792
The operation of the building will get higher priority than some of the things that maybe are aspirational.

750
01:01:37,192 --> 01:01:37,652
You know that.

751
01:01:38,554 --> 01:01:44,641
So if you decide that certain things aren't something you want to fund, then you say, well, put that off for a couple of years.

752
01:01:45,122 --> 01:01:46,844
But certainly, you're going to face a roof.

753
01:01:47,305 --> 01:01:48,907
Certainly, you're going to face technology.

754
01:01:49,267 --> 01:01:52,611
Certainly, you're going to deal with other systems, heating systems, and other things like that.

755
01:01:53,112 --> 01:01:56,436
And if we don't get in the game now, it'll be longer.

756
01:01:57,647 --> 01:01:58,767
before we get funding.

757
01:01:59,187 --> 01:02:06,629
And if we don't, and if the funding dries up because of the Commonwealth not being able to keep things moving, you see the green line, other things like that.

758
01:02:06,669 --> 01:02:10,150
We talk about these things and it keeps getting pushed off, keeps getting pushed off.

759
01:02:10,850 --> 01:02:16,711
Let's get in the game and then you can decide whether or not it's something you desire as a priority.

760
01:02:16,831 --> 01:02:17,911
That's what we need to look at.

761
01:02:18,411 --> 01:02:20,192
I think it's my job to put it in front of you.

762
01:02:20,612 --> 01:02:26,913
I hope it's your job to, or I hope it's your willingness to let me find out what's possible going forward.

763
01:02:28,173 --> 01:02:37,298
So Mr. Superintendent, just getting back to some of the building deficiencies, would you agree that the restrooms at the high school are a deficiency of Meffitt High School?

764
01:02:38,399 --> 01:02:42,621
I would agree that restrooms are something that should be addressed, yes.

765
01:02:43,562 --> 01:02:45,023
How come they're not part of the SOI?

766
01:02:45,083 --> 01:02:46,944
Because they're part of the general building envelope.

767
01:02:47,284 --> 01:02:48,685
That's something that we can talk about.

768
01:02:49,025 --> 01:02:49,925
They're part of the plumbing.

769
01:02:49,945 --> 01:02:51,787
They're part of the heating system, believe it or not.

770
01:02:52,107 --> 01:02:54,388
It's all part of the same consideration.

771
01:02:54,742 --> 01:03:01,304
And just because something isn't written here doesn't mean we can't talk about it with the team that comes out from MSBA.

772
01:03:01,724 --> 01:03:05,045
If we think of other things, we can say, you know, by the way, we'd like you to look at this as well.

773
01:03:05,825 --> 01:03:13,568
This is to get them, to give them an idea of which communities are interested in seeking partnership with the state.

774
01:03:14,388 --> 01:03:17,389
So just so I understand, you brought up a good point.

775
01:03:17,769 --> 01:03:22,150
So after the April 7th deadline, you're stating that we can add stuff to the SOI?

776
01:03:22,650 --> 01:03:24,071
We can talk to them about it, yes.

777
01:03:24,621 --> 01:03:27,102
Not talk, we can add stuff after the deadline.

778
01:03:27,682 --> 01:03:28,683
We can talk stuff, yes.

779
01:03:29,583 --> 01:03:30,603
We can talk with them about it.

780
01:03:30,643 --> 01:03:32,184
Maybe they'll let us add, maybe they won't.

781
01:03:32,484 --> 01:03:36,265
But I'm sure they would consider some of the things that we would bring up.

782
01:03:36,866 --> 01:03:47,970
With all due respect, Mr. Superintendent, I've been an advocate for a number of years regarding the cleanliness and the deplorable condition of the bathrooms at the high school.

783
01:03:48,810 --> 01:03:53,172
And there's been some headway made, I have to give credit, there's been some headway made

784
01:03:53,565 --> 01:03:55,186
with the water bubblers and so forth.

785
01:03:55,567 --> 01:04:04,174
But many of the restrooms at the high school are locked down, not because we don't have the manpower to supervise them, it's because they're in deplorable condition, Mr. Superintendent.

786
01:04:04,834 --> 01:04:07,557
And this is coming from firsthand knowledge.

787
01:04:08,217 --> 01:04:15,043
And I can tell you that the fact that it's not addressed in a deficiency in this program and say, well, it's covered under other things.

788
01:04:15,667 --> 01:04:19,969
I think is not adequately addressing the deficiencies that we have at that school.

789
01:04:21,029 --> 01:04:31,774
It may not be educational in nature, but what I can tell you is that there are kids at the high school that will hold in going to the restroom a whole day because they're so filthy dirty.

790
01:04:32,154 --> 01:04:33,335
And you can't get toilet paper.

791
01:04:33,495 --> 01:04:34,195
There's no soap.

792
01:04:34,455 --> 01:04:35,536
There's no paper towels.

793
01:04:36,616 --> 01:04:38,277
There's no doors on the urinals.

794
01:04:38,738 --> 01:04:45,802
And I'm just telling you reality, Mr. Superintendent, because you have your own private bathroom and probably don't frequent other restrooms in the building.

795
01:04:46,222 --> 01:04:52,646
And I could just tell you that from what I hear from students, Mr. Superintendent, is that's what's happening up there.

796
01:04:53,266 --> 01:04:56,388
And I'm saddened to see that it's not addressed in the SOI.

797
01:04:57,249 --> 01:05:03,833
But if you're telling me it could be added at a later date, that's fine, and I hope it does get added, because that would be my addition.

798
01:05:04,802 --> 01:05:06,423
I guess I'm a stakeholder.

799
01:05:06,984 --> 01:05:14,529
I certainly would bring that up in any kind of discussion, but I can tell you that I don't share your full assessment of our bathroom facilities.

800
01:05:14,549 --> 01:05:21,134
There may be a few that need some additional work, but there's a lot of them that work very well and are in good shape and are being cleaned on a regular basis.

801
01:05:21,154 --> 01:05:22,174
That's my exact point.

802
01:05:23,015 --> 01:05:26,778
I know you don't share them and that's why they've been in deplorable condition for so many years.

803
01:05:27,478 --> 01:05:29,820
That's my exact point, Mr. Superintendent.

804
01:05:30,961 --> 01:05:32,362
So we can go back and forth on that.

805
01:05:34,140 --> 01:05:40,583
And also, Mr. Superintendent, you were here several months back when we were talking about safety at the high school.

806
01:05:40,623 --> 01:05:42,984
We had a great debate going back and forth.

807
01:05:43,484 --> 01:05:56,310
And I see you mentioned in the SOI that you have the inability to close off certain parts of the building and have the inability to keep it cordoned off to people from outside and so forth.

808
01:05:56,830 --> 01:06:01,712
I'm glad to see that you're finally admitting that there is a security issue at the high school.

809
01:06:02,386 --> 01:06:18,254
and that there is concern, Mr. Superintendent, with access to that building throughout the course of the day, and that we've been unable to control the access, and I'm glad to see that you're offering some solutions to that effect, Mr. Superintendent.

810
01:06:18,354 --> 01:06:21,156
